content.content: Comment:

The manufacturer has not determined the efficacy of this test in "Critically ill" patients. UMass Memorial Medical Center defines "Critically ill" patients for the purpose of blood glucose monitoring (BGM) by glucometer, as patients meeting one or more of the following criteria:
Hypotension- non-ICU patients (systolic blood pressure Less than 90 mmHg) due to shock
Hypotension -ICU patients (Mean Arterial Pressure (MAP) <60 mmHg or systolic blood pressure < 90 mmHg due to shock
Patients receiving Vasopressors (phenylephrine, vasopressin or norepinephrine)
Anasarca
In all locations, BGM test results should not be relied upon in the above situations, unless these results confirmed with lab-based glucose values.

University of Massachusetts Heart and Vascular Center of Excellence
Heart and Vascular Invasive Laboratory Electrophysiology Procedure Report
Patient Information:
Name: Oscar Williams
Age: 63 y.o.
Gender: male
Study Date: 2024-01-23
Staff:
Surgeon(s):
Eric Davis, MD
HV Nurse: Dina Generelli; Ellen Kane, RN
HV Nurse Practitioner: Eric, NP
HV X-Ray Technologist: Jonathan D Lieske, RT(R)
HV Documenter: Zachary O'Connor, RN
Patient History:
The patient is a 63 y.o. male with a history of atrial flutter on
eliquis, ESRD on HD, CVA, T2DM, HLD presented for placement of tunnel
dialysis catheter.
Patient presented to the ED 2024-01-19 for non functioning dialysis
catheter. His last HD was 2024-01-17. Was unable to get his Friday session
as the catheter was blocked. EKG on 5/19 shows NSR, RBBB and 2:1 AV block.
He presents to the EP lab for implantation of a dual chamber permanent
pacemaker.
Conclusions:
1 .Successful implantation of a Boston Scientific dual chamber pacemaker.
2. Tyrex antibiotic pouch applied for prophylaxis
Recommendations:
1. Wound check in 1-2 week weeks.
2. Follow up in device clinic in 4-6 weeks.
Methods:
The patient was transported to the UMass Memorial EP lab in a
post-absorptive, non-sedated state. Informed consent was obtained prior
to the procedure. Two peripheral IVs were in place. Continuous
electrocardiography, blood pressure and SaO2 monitoring was initiated and
hands-free cardioversion patch electrodes were positioned on the chest.
Deep sedation was administered per the anesthesiology team.
Prior to procedure start, 2g IV Ancef (Cefazolin) was administered.
The chest was prepped & draped in the usual sterile fashion. 1% polocaine
was used as local anesthetic. Using a #10 blade a 4 cm incision was made
in the right infraclavicular region. Using sharp and blunt dissection, the
subcutaneous tissue was dissected down to the prepectoral fascia and a
pocket was created. Venous access was established in the right medial
axillary vein under fluoroscopic guidance. A J wire was inserted into
the IVC to confirm position.
A lead was positioned in the mid interventricular septum using a dilator
peel away sheath, standard technique, and fluoroscopic guidance. Adequate
pacing parameters were achieved and the lead was subsequently sewn down to

paragraph.content: Procedure Details
University of Massachusetts Heart and Vascular Center of Excellence
Heart and Vascular Invasive Laboratory Vascular Procedure Report
Clinical History: Oscar Williams is a 63 y.o. male with a poorly functioning tunneled dialysis catheter.
Procedure(s) Performed:
Procedure(s):
Tunnel Dialysis Catheter Exchange with possible use of Moderate Sedation
Surgeon(s) and Role:
* Louis, MD - Primary
* Kimberly Palmer, MD - Resident - Assisting
Resident Surgeon: As Above.
Statement of attending's presence: The attending surgeon, Louis, MD, was present and supervised the entire care.
Staff:
HV Nurse: Dina Generelli; Noah Blair, RN
HV X-Ray Technologist: Kellie A Sheehan, RT(R)
Anesthesia and Moderate Sedation:

Pre-sedation history and evaluation revealed no contraindications to moderate sedation. The patient received lidocaine, benzodiazepines and/or opioids, the dosing of which is documented in the patient's permanent medical record. The procedural nursing staff and Louis, MD monitored the patient's level of consciousness and physiologic status continuously throughout the procedure. Total intra-service moderate sedation time was 0 Hr 37 Min 53 Sec minutes.
ASA: ASA status not filed in the log.
Estimated Blood Loss: No blood loss documented.
Implants:
As documented in the patient's electronic lines, drains, and airways record.
Radiographic Findings:
The previous tunneled dialysis catheter was removed intact.
The new 23cm tunneled dialysis catheter is in place with the tip in the right atrium.
The catheter course is without twisting or kinking.
No evidence of pneumothorax was appreciated on fluoroscopy.
The tunneled dialysis catheter is ready for immediate use.
Procedure in detail:

After patient identification and informed consent, the patient was taken to the angiography suite and placed in supine position on the table. Physiologic monitoring was initiated. Moderate sedation for patient comfort and analgesia was provided at the direction and constant supervision of the attending surgeon. The surgical site was cleaned and draped in a sterile fashion using chlorhexidine. A timeout was called.

Local anesthetic was injected into the skin and subcutaneous tissue overlying the existing venotomy site. The previous physician was opened sharply, and then the existing dialysis catheter circumferentially dissected and extravasated for short distance. The catheter was divided between clamps. A guidewire was advanced through the catheter under continuous fluoroscopic guidance into the IVC. The intracorporeal portion of the catheter was then removed over the wire wall pressure was held. Serial dilation was performed and then a peel-away sheath placed over the wire.

The location of the catheter tunnel exit site was approximated. Additional local anesthetic was then injected at the catheter exit site and along the course of the tunnel. A counterincision was made sharply, and then the catheter was tunneled to the venous access site. The catheter was inserted through the peel-away sheath which was subsequently removed. A completion venogram was performed, the catheter course and tip position were found to be satisfactory

Both catheter lumens were found to return blood freely and flushed without resistance. The catheter lumens were packed with normal saline. The catheter hubs were capped. The access site incision was closed in subcuticular fashion with absorbable suture, and dressed with Dermabond. The catheter was then secured to the skin with sutures, and the catheter exit site dressed with a chlorhexidine impregnated dressing. The extracorporal portion of the previous dialysis catheter was then removed by blunt dissection of the cuff. The removal site was dressed with a sterile dressing. The patient tolerated the procedure well, there were no apparent immediate complications. The patient was transferred to the recovery area in satisfactory condition.
Impression:
Successful exchange of a tunneled dialysis catheter. The catheter is ready for immediate use.
Complications: None
Post Procedure Plan/Follow up: OK to use TDC for HD
